  "experiments_summary": "The study uses physics-based models (PBMs) to generate training data for plasma etching of PMMA in a GEC reference reactor operating in ICP mode. For single-gas systems (O2 and Ar), 4000 data points each were generated via PBM simulations with inputs of coil power (50-2000 W) and pressure (10-70 mTorr), split 60-20-20% for training/validation/testing. Simple feedforward neural networks (FNNs) with 3 hidden layers were trained for each gas, achieving R² scores of 0.84 (O2) and 0.96 (Ar). For Ar/O2 mixtures, 4758 PBM data points were generated with additional input of Ar fraction (0.01-0.96). Two testing strategies were employed: Testgrid (withholding top 25% of power/pressure values) and Testthresh (training only on xAr > 0.2 cases). The proposed architecture uses pre-trained single-gas networks (frozen during training) to generate features, which are concatenated with gas fractions to form node attributes in a complete two-node graph. This graph is processed by a GraphSAGE layer with ReLU activation followed by a linear layer to predict 10 radial etching rates. Experiments evaluated four feature extraction strategies: network outputs, last hidden layer, second-to-last hidden layer, and first hidden layer. The method was compared against an FNN baseline and also tested against GCN and GAT architectures. Training used weighted MSE loss to handle radial variation in etching rates, with L2 regularization and early stopping. All data were min-max normalized to [0,1]."
